<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="28" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1438,1098,1820]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,276,1098,1124]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Characters of the subfamily Limnesiinae (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Cook" box="[862,1002,1098,1124]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" refString="Cook, D. R. (1974) Water mites genera and subgenera. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 21, 1 - 1858. Goldschmidt, T. (2004) Studies on Neotropical Limnesiidae Thor, 1910 Part III: Protolimnesiinae sensu K. Viets, 1953 (Acari, Actinedida, Hydrachnidia). Archiv fur Hydrobiologie, Supplement, 151, 69 - 123." type="journal article" year="1974">
Cook 
<number box="[936,1002,1098,1124]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1974.0">1974</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Body soft and papillate. Edges of epimera and genital flaps thickened. Genital flaps fused anteriorly and posterioly in male and the flaps movable in female. Three pairs of elongated acetabula present, the margin of acetabula thickened and irregularly shaped; the second acetabulum parallel, posterior to and somewhat underneath the third acetabulum; the first acetabulum approximately at a right angle with second and third acetabulum in male. E 
<number box="[1421,1435,1253,1279]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="4.0">4</number>
located on the third epimera. Peg-like seta on ventral side of P-II. Legs without pronounced sexual dimorphism; swimming hairs present.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[197,833,1368,1395]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1438,1098,1820]" box="[197,833,1368,1395]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,349,1368,1394]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">
<typeStatus box="[197,256,1368,1394]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Type</typeStatus>
species
</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Yi &amp; Jin" authorityName="Yi &amp; Jin" box="[367,735,1369,1395]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Orientilimnesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sinica" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[367,628,1369,1394]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Orientilimnesia sinica</emphasis>
Yi &amp; Jin
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[742,833,1369,1395]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[197,1410,1407,1434]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1438,1098,1820]" box="[197,1410,1407,1434]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,332,1407,1433]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Etymology</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName box="[347,455,1408,1433]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Limnesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[347,455,1408,1433]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Limnesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like mite from the oriental. “Orienti-”, from “Orientalis” in latin, means oriental.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="28" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1438,1098,1820]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,311,1446,1472]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Remarks</emphasis>
: The number and position of genital acetabula are used as characters for the diagnosis of genera and species of water mites (
<bibRefCitation author="Cook" box="[475,609,1485,1511]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" refString="Cook, D. R. (1974) Water mites genera and subgenera. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 21, 1 - 1858. Goldschmidt, T. (2004) Studies on Neotropical Limnesiidae Thor, 1910 Part III: Protolimnesiinae sensu K. Viets, 1953 (Acari, Actinedida, Hydrachnidia). Archiv fur Hydrobiologie, Supplement, 151, 69 - 123." type="journal article" year="1974">
Cook 
<number box="[548,609,1485,1511]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1974.0">1974</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Barr" box="[621,739,1485,1511]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" refString="Barr, D. W. (1982) Comparative morphology of the genital acetabula of aquatic mites (Acari, Prostigmata): Hydrachnoidea, Eylaoidea, Hydryphantoidea and Lebertioidea. Journal of Natural History, 16, 147 - 160." type="journal article" year="1982">
Barr 
<number box="[681,739,1485,1511]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1982.0">1982</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).Within 
<taxonomicName box="[844,989,1485,1511]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Limnesiidae</taxonomicName>
the number of acetabula is three pairs to many; their shape is round, oval, elongated or lobated; they are usually situated on genital flaps or plates (
<bibRefCitation author="Cook" box="[159,291,1562,1588]" pageId="1" pageNumber="31" refString="Cook, D. R. (1974) Water mites genera and subgenera. Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 21, 1 - 1858. Goldschmidt, T. (2004) Studies on Neotropical Limnesiidae Thor, 1910 Part III: Protolimnesiinae sensu K. Viets, 1953 (Acari, Actinedida, Hydrachnidia). Archiv fur Hydrobiologie, Supplement, 151, 69 - 123." type="journal article" year="1974">
Cook 
<number box="[231,291,1562,1588]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1974.0">1974</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) but may also lay under genital flaps beside the gonopore (Goldschmidt 
<number box="[1144,1208,1562,1588]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="2004.0">2004</number>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1438,1098,1820]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">
Within the 
<taxonomicName box="[330,476,1601,1627]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Limnesiidae</taxonomicName>
two species have elongated acetabula: 
<taxonomicName authority="Lundblad, 1953" authorityName="Lundblad" authorityYear="1953" box="[943,1370,1601,1627]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Limnesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longipora">
<emphasis box="[943,1175,1601,1626]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Limnesia longipora</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lundblad" box="[1183,1370,1601,1627]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" refString="Lundblad, O. (1953) Die Hydracarinenfauna von Columbia. Arkiv for Zoologi (Ser. 2), 5, 435 - 585." type="journal article" year="1953">
Lundblad, 
<number box="[1311,1370,1601,1627]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1953.0">1953</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,223,1640,1666]" name="Brazil" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Lundblad, 1936" authorityName="Lundblad" authorityYear="1936" box="[278,739,1640,1666]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Limnesides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="epimeratus">
<emphasis box="[278,547,1640,1665]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Limnesides epimeratus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Lundblad" box="[554,739,1640,1666]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" refString="Lundblad, O. (1936) Dritte Mitteilung uber Wassermilben aus Santa Catharina in Sudbrasilien. Zoologischer Anzeiger, 116, 200 - 211." type="journal article" year="1936">
Lundblad, 
<number box="[680,739,1640,1666]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1936.0">1936</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[810,929,1640,1666]" name="Colombia" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Colombia</collectingCountry>
. However, all these taxa differ significantly from 
<taxonomicName box="[219,411,1679,1704]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Orientilimnesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis box="[219,411,1679,1704]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Orientilimnesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[419,532,1678,1704]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in the arrangement of acetabula. In 
<taxonomicName box="[979,1117,1679,1704]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Limnesides" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[979,1117,1679,1704]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Limnesides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1178,1290,1679,1704]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Limnesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1178,1290,1679,1704]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Limnesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the second acetabulum is located between the first and the third one or, in some case, at the same level as the third one (e.g., 
<taxonomicName authority="Viets, 1935" authorityName="Viets" authorityYear="1935" box="[229,644,1756,1782]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Limnesia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="papillosa">
<emphasis box="[229,481,1756,1781]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Limnesia papillosa</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Viets" box="[490,644,1756,1782]" pageId="1" pageNumber="32" refString="Viets, K. (1935) Die Wasermilben von Sumatra, Java und Bali nach den Ergebnissen der Deutschen Limnologischen Sunda-Expedition. Archiv fur Hydrobiologie, Supplement, 13, 484 - 738." type="journal article" year="1935">
Viets, 
<number box="[576,644,1756,1782]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1935.0">1935</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, the adults were reported by Lundblad in 
<number box="[1201,1270,1756,1782]" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" value="1971.0">1971</number>
), whereas in 
<taxonomicName box="[151,335,1795,1820]" class="Arachnida" family="Limnesiidae" genus="Orientilimnesia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="1" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,335,1795,1820]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="28">Orientilimnesia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the second acetabulum is posterior to and underneath the third one.
</paragraph>
